{{split|Latino|Gender neutrality in Spanish and Portuguese|Hispanic and Latino American politics in the United States|date=November 2017}}
{{wiktionary|Latinx}}
'''Latinx''' is a [[Gender neutrality|gender neutral]] term often used in lieu of ''[[Latino]]'' or ''Latina'' (referencing [[Latin America]]n cultural or racial identity).
The ''-x'' replaces the standard ''o/a'' ending in [[West Iberian languages|Spanish and Portuguese]]
forming nouns of the masculine and feminine genderes, respectively.
The term is a [[political neologism]], reportedly first used online in 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oed.com/view/Entry/106153?rskey=e09vnd&result=1&isAdvanced=false|title=Home : Oxford English Dictionary|website=www.oed.com|language=en|access-date=2017-04-22}}</ref> The term has gain popularity in social media, yet, is mostly used community activist and in higher education settings by students, faculty, staff, and some administrators that seek to advocate for individuals that live in the borderlands of gender <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Salinas|first1=Cristobal|last2=Lozano|first2=Adele|title=Mapping and recontextualizing the evolution of the term Latinx: An environmental scanning in higher education|journal=Journal of Latinos and Education|date=2017|doi=10.1080/15348431.2017.1390464|url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/15348431.2017.1390464?scroll=top&needAccess=true#.WhQdpN411v4.twitter|accessdate=22 November 2017}}</ref> In their work, Salinas and Lozano (2017)<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Salinas|first1=Cristobal|last2=Lozano|first2=Adele|title=Mapping and recontextualizing the evolution of the term Latinx: An environmental scanning in higher education|journal=Journal of Latinos and Education|date=2017|doi=10.1080/15348431.2017.1390464|url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/15348431.2017.1390464?scroll=top&needAccess=true#.WhQdpN411v4.twitter|accessdate=22 November 2017}}</ref>  stated that the term is influenced by Mexican indigenous communities of people. 

According to [[Google Trends]], interest in the term peaked in 2016, when it began to be actively advocated for in certain online media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://trends.google.com/trends/explore?q=latinx|title=Google Trends|website=Google Trends|access-date=2017-04-22}}</ref>
It has gained traction among advocacy groups [[Intersectionality|combining]] racial and gender identity politics.

An alternative term is '''Latin@''' where the [[@]] symbol is taken to represent a combination of ''a'' and ''o'' in a single character. This variant is somewhat older, in use since the 1990s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/heymigente/what-is-latinx-and-afrolatinx-c05a63b5a3d4|title=What is Latinx and AfroLatinx?|date=2016-08-18|website=#HeyMiGente|access-date=2017-04-23}}</ref> 
Yet another, more recent, variant is '''Latine''', where the vowel ''e'' is taken as a "neutral" alternative to either ''a'' or ''o''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://trends.google.com/trends/explore?q=latin|title=Google Trends|website=Google Trends|access-date=2017-04-23}}
{{Cite journal|last=Gamio|first=Arlene|title=Latinx: A Brief Guidebook|url=https://www.academia.edu/29657615/Latinx_A_Brief_Guidebook|language=en}}</ref>

However, it has not been officially accepted as linguistically correct<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://swarthmorephoenix.com/2015/11/19/the-argument-against-the-use-of-the-term-latinx/|title=The argument against the use of the term “Latinx”|work=The Phoenix|access-date=2017-11-15|language=en-US}}</ref>. Some refuse to use the term as "Latinx doesn't roll of the tongue in the Spanish language." <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/why-people-are-using-the-term-latinx_us_57753328e4b0cc0fa136a159|title=Why People Are Using The Term 'Latinx'|last=Ramirez|first=Tanisha Love|date=2016-07-05|work=Huffington Post|access-date=2017-11-15|last2=Blay|first2=Zeba|language=en-US}}</ref>

==Usage examples==
{{trivia|date=November 2017}}
The term appears in print, also in 2016, in the context of  [[identity politics]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wo_JDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA4&lpg=PA4&dq=latinx+term&source=bl&ots=L5g17TxdjY&sig=vSrZT34nOVqLAOU9gwAmInex0CQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjBuJyF2a7TAhWlzIMKHXszBSY4HhDoAQgpMAI#v=onepage&q=latinx%20term&f=false|title=An Examination of Latinx LGBT Populations Across the United States: Intersections of Race and Sexuality|last=Jr|first=Antonio (Jay) Pastrana|last2=Battle|first2=Juan|last3=Harris|first3=Angelique|date=2016-12-22|publisher=Springer|isbn=9781137560742|language=en}}</ref>

At [[Princeton University]], the "Princeton University Latinx Perspective Organization" was founded in 2016 to “unify Princeton’s diverse Latinx community."<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://pulatinx.wixsite.com/pulpo|title=Home {{!}} Princeton University Latinx Perspectives Organization|work=Home {{!}} Princeton University Latinx Perspectives Organization|access-date=2017-04-23}}</ref> 
Student run organizations that utilize Latinx in their title also exist at other institutions, including [[Oberlin College]] and [[Oberlin Conservatory of Music|Conservatory]], [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]], and [[Iowa State University]], highlighting the widespread usage of the term at the undergraduate level.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lsp.unc.edu/student-organizations/|title=Student Organizations {{!}} UNC Latina/o Studies Program|website=lsp.unc.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2017-04-23}}
{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuorg.iastate.edu/site/2105|title=Iowa State University - Student Organizations|website=www.stuorg.iastate.edu|language=en-us|access-date=2017-04-23}}
{{Cite web|url=https://new.oberlin.edu/office/multicultural-resource-center/student-resources/latinx-resources/latinx-student-organizations|title=Latinx Student Organizations {{!}} Multicultural Resource Center {{!}} Oberlin College|website=new.oberlin.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-04-23}}</ref> 

The term has since been discussed in publications by 
Pastrana (2016),  Battle (2016) and Valdes (2017).<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7HVgDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA15&lpg=PA15&dq=latinx+term&source=bl&ots=m64kehTNPC&sig=m8elOQQZNCn-rmBvEoWw4kCbnLM&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi8sLKX2a7TAhUp_4MKHW4DAYI4KBDoAQhAMAY#v=onepage&q=latinx%20term&f=false|title=Diasporic Blackness: The Life and Times of Arturo Alfonso Schomburg|last=Valdés|first=Vanessa K.|date=2017-03-15|publisher=SUNY Press|isbn=9781438465159|language=en}}
{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wo_JDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA8&dq=an+examination+of+latinx&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiEuuO42bnTAhXM6CYKHWVDDYoQ6AEIJDAA#v=onepage&q=an%20examination%20of%20latinx&f=false|title=An Examination of Latinx LGBT Populations Across the United States: Intersections of Race and Sexuality|last=Jr|first=Antonio (Jay) Pastrana|last2=Battle|first2=Juan|last3=Harris|first3=Angelique|date=2016-12-22|publisher=Springer|isbn=9781137560742|language=en}}
{{Cite web|url=http://www.aaihs.org/thinking-about-an-x/|title=Thinking About the ‘X’ – AAIHS|website=www.aaihs.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-04-23}}</ref>

Scharrón-del Río and   Aja (2015) have traced the use of Latinx in authors Beatriz Llenin Figueroa, Jaime Géliga Quiñones,   Yuderkys Espinosa Miñoso and Adriana Gallegos Dextre.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.latinorebels.com/2015/12/05/the-case-for-latinx-why-intersectionality-is-not-a-choice/|title=The Case FOR ‘Latinx’: Why Intersectionality Is Not a Choice|last=Río|first=María R. Scharrón-del|last2=Aja|first2=Alan A.|date=2015-12-05|website=Latino Rebels|access-date=2017-04-24}}</ref> 

In a proposed 2016 bill to the US Senate, the Community Outreach and Engagement Coordinator at [[Planned Parenthood]] of Southern [[New England]] utilized the word Latinx when advocating for the passing of Senate Bill 147.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cga.ct.gov/2016/heddata/tmy/2016SB-00147-R000301-Mayra%20Sierra,%20Community%20Outreach%20&%20Engagement%20Coordinator,%20Planned%20Parenthood%20of%20Southern%20New%20England-TMY.PDF|title=Testimony of Mayra Sierra|last=|first=|date=April 22, 2017|website=www.cga.ct.gov|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>  

